Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Charles L. Grable in Court with Attorney Liesl E. Nelson.  ADA William H. Thorie appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Case called at 2:37 p.m.  Atty. Nelson presents Court w/Plea Questionnaire.  ADA Thorie advises Court of agreement; Amended Information charging one count of misdemeanor battery.  Requesting sentencing W/H w/one year Probation, requesting conditions.  Atty. Nelson informs Court of Psych. eval., testing w/VA and cooperation w/DHS.  Court questions Defendant; advises of amended charge and possible penalties.  Advises of rights.  Defendant understands.  Court questions military service.  Defendant pleads Guilty to Misdemeanor Battery.  Atty. Nelson stipulates to facts.  Court makes findings; Defendant has freely, vol., and intelligently entered plea.  Court adjudicates Defendant Guilty.  ADA Thorie and Atty. Nelson make statements.  Defendant declines statement.  Court questions; Defendant advises of working w/VA.  Court questions SW Kim Stensland, she advises.  Court sentences Defendant, Withheld.  Court orders one year Probation; specific conditions of Probation will be set by Agent.  Court orders court costs of $443, this includes DNA surcharge.  Court advises of right to appeal.

Not guilty plea received by the courtInformation Filed with the Court and a copy is given to the defendant.    Defendant has a copy of the information  and waives reading of the information.    Defendant enters not guilty plea at preliminary hearing.    Not guilty plea received by the court.  The bond will continue as ordered.   Pretrial Conference to be set.  See JA for date.

11:48 a.m.  Defendant Charles L. Grable in court with attorney Liesl E. Nelson.  Sean Edward Froelich appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Froelich calls River Falls P.D. Officer Steven Thomas.  Thomas is sworn and takes the witness stand.  Froelich examines Thomas.  Thomas identifies the defendant.  Nelson x-exams Thomas.  Court finds probable cause and binds defendant over.
Def has knowingly and willingly waived his rights to have his preliminary hearing within 20 days.
